"Ironbane", despite sounding like an epithet for a legendary warrior in a fantasy setting, is this universe's English word for "railroad". Much like in OTL, they were first built by one Jorn Stefanson, with the first being constructed between Leyrpool and Manchester and opened in 1830. Some other English words I found pretty interesting are "witship" for science and "wiselust" for philosophy.

by Hatsunia » Sat Nov 21, 2020 12:02 pm

The Republican Party didn't enact the Southern strategy in this timeline and the Democratic Party remained as a "Dixiecrat" party, and by the 1980s, had become a minor third party. The two main parties of the US became the Republican and Progressive Parties. But due to war exhaustion and economic issues, a counter-culture based on a combination of white nationalism and socialism had formed. In the 2010s, Jimmy Webster was the first Democrat elected since the 1950s. He was impeached because of illegally modified and unregistered firearms, and Soviet and Confederate memorabilia was found in his house. Many workers joined a general strike in protest of his impeachment, but it was unsuccessful at the time.

Tokyo has charged headlong into the “hardware future,” still churning out physical devices, valuing manufacturing over coding.

And for what it is worth, that is one of the best things about Hatsunia that I have learned. The acknowledgement that they believe and think that hardware plays an important part, and it's not just software that we need to drastically improve. Sure, the humble screen can only go so far but at the end of the day, software can only push something so far before it hits the limitation of a hardware.

No amount of software will dramatically increase the lifespan of a screen, and no amount of optimised software will help if a mouse is crappy.

by Khoronzon » Mon Nov 23, 2020 10:34 am

Japan is the world's largest economy in their universe, with a GDP of $7.76 trillion (I'm assuming USD isn't actually the standard in this world, which makes me wonder which currency would hold that position in its absence), and one of the five main Great Powers that count among the High Formanship, which I take to be their world's rough equivalent of the G7. In addition to the Japanese Archipelago, it holds the entirety of the Korean Peninsula, the island of Formosa/Taiwan, and the southern half of Sakhalin. It has waged three major wars against China since 1853, and during the Second World War, which was initially the Second Sino-Japanese War or Twithe Chineish-Japanish Crig, they dropped a nuke on Nanjing, which I find morbidly funny. Perhaps a tad more merciful than what actually happened.
